The paper deals with the metric properties of graphs, specifically the slimness of graphs. This topic is closely related to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and computational geometry (cs.CG). The layering partition technique used in the paper is a common tool in graph theory and algorithms, which falls under the category of data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the slimness of certain families of graphs, such as $k$-chordal graphs and AT-free graphs, which are topics in graph theory and combinatorics (cs.GT). Finally, the paper mentions the use of slimness in network design and optimization, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
